    <p>
      <bold>Summary</bold>
    </p>
    <p> The manuscript presents a novel tool (MarkerScan) that identifies, separates, and assembles sequences for distinct taxa found within mixed-species genome sequencing datasets. The rationale for developing this tool is that many sequencing datasets contain numerous sequencing reads from non-target species. The contaminating sequences can arise from errors in sample preparation or through tight biological associations of taxa with a target-species. </p>
    <p> To avoid the buildup of mislabeled sequences in public archives, various tools have been developed to identify and filter non-target contaminants. MarkerScan distinguishes itself from previous tools in at least two ways. First, MarkerScan uses the universal marker small subunit rRNA (SSU) to screen for contaminating taxa prior to classification. Second, rather than discarding the non-target reads, MarkerScan will produce high-quality assemblies for non-target species identified within the sequencing dataset.</p>
    <p> The description of the MarkerScan is thorough, clear, and direct.</p>
    <p> This reviewer has no issues with any step of the workflow or its description in the manuscript.  The example output data provided in the zenodo repository does not provide code to recreate the analysis, but it does give them an example of the full output of the tool for the numerous examples included in the text.</p>
    <p> The authors provide examples showing the utility of the MarkerScan in identifying, separating, and assembling non-target species genomes from datasets that range in complexity. The authors point out that MarkerScan’s unique order of operations (identification of species composition first, then sequence similarity search and binning) greatly reduces the high rate of false positive assignments characteristic of some other methods - especially for examples of “low complexity metagenomes”. This is key because that is exactly the kind of sequencing projects the tool is designed to work with and other tools are prone to over partitioning data. In contrast, the authors point out that the tool is less appropriate for “high-complexity metagenomes”. </p>
    <p>
      <bold>Major concerns</bold>
    </p>
    <p> None.</p>
    <p>
      <bold>Minor concerns</bold>
      <list list-type="order">
        <list-item>
          <p>The github repo appears to not align with the paper on all points e.g. “MarkerScan uses a set of reference databases, which are automatically downloaded when absent or more than one month old.” Github says 180 days? Also, the schematic overview figure in the repo is less clear than the one in the manuscript. </p>
        </list-item>
        <list-item>
          <p>Figure 2A+B are somewhat hard to discern because of the large number of points with F1 scores of 1.00. The authors might consider plotting these scores as a heatmap instead with tools on the x-axis and F1-scores shown on a color scale. However, the current visualization is sufficient . It could easily be the case that small differences near 1 would be indiscernible with the proposed heat map. </p>
        </list-item>
      </list>
    </p>
    <p>
      <bold>Specific notes:</bold>
      <list list-type="order">
        <list-item>
          <p>Introduction - paragraph2 - sentence 1: Consider changing “Although contamination can be introduced during many stages of handling of the sample…” to “Although contamination can be introduced during many stages of sample handling…”</p>
        </list-item>
        <list-item>
          <p>Introduction - paragraph6: Consider breaking the sentence starting with “MarkerScan does this by first identifying the taxa likely to be present in a sample through…” into two or more sentences. </p>
        </list-item>
        <list-item>
          <p>Methods -  paragraph2 - sentence2: Consider changing “An HMM profile…” to “A profile hidden Markov model (pHMM)...”</p>
        </list-item>
      </list>
    </p>
