    <p>The manuscript presents MarkerScan, a novel tool for identifying and assembling genomes of cobionts present in mixed-species genome sequencing datasets. The approach leverages the identification of small subunit rRNA (SSU) sequences to classify sequences and separate non-target genomes from the target species. MarkerScan not only provides an effective strategy for the contamination issues in public databases caused by mislabeled sequences but also facilitates the generation of high-quality genomes for non-target organisms.</p>
    <p> Majors:</p>
    <p> 1. The introduction would benefit from a clearer statement of the problem being addressed. The introduction emphasized the significance of addressing the contamination issue in public databases due to mislabeled sequences and detailed the approaches that might be employed in identifying non-target sequences. However, it is essential to articulate more explicitly the challenges faced by existing tools in identifying and assembling non-target genomes within mixed-species datasets.</p>
    <p> 2. The manuscript has indicated that the five datasets selected reflect the complexity observed in target species and their cobionts in nature. However, the selection of species primarily focuses on a relatively narrow range of ecosystems and host species. Does this selection fully represent the diversity and complexity encountered in biodiversity genomics projects? Could the choice of species from different ecological environments influence the detection performance of MarkerScan?</p>
    <p> 3. The manuscript compares the performance of MarkerScan with other detection tools using several case analyses of mock and natural communities. However, these case studies seem somewhat fragmented, making it challenging to synthesize and understand MarkerScan’s advantages comprehensively. Incorporating systematic analyses and comparisons of MarkerScan against other tools through statistical charts could provide a more intuitive and clear depiction for readers. Furthermore, the manuscript lacks a comparative analysis of detection tools in terms of memory usage and runtime.</p>
    <p> 4. Does prioritizing species composition determination before sequence similarity searches and binning introduce a detection bias, potentially increasing the false-negative rate? Beyond awaiting the increase of metagenome-derived assembled genomes and the development of sequence similarity-based prokaryotic taxonomy methods, are there alternative strategies for refining MarkerScan to more accurately identify species in high-complexity metagenomes?</p>
