    <p>Vancaester and Blaxter present a new software for dealing with mixed samples in genome sequencing projects. The paper is well-written with well-placed analyses provide sufficient proof that underscores the utility of the new software. I have only small suggestions that the Authors may consider when revising their MS.</p>
    <p> Possibly the largest concern is that MarkerScan searches at the family level only. Fixing the search at the family level has the risk of certain taxa not having any representatives from the same family in sequence databases. While this is unlikely to be a problem in metazoans or plants, in several protist groups it may be. Is there an easy fix around? If not this might need to be acknowledged.</p>
    <p> In the Results section, it would be helpful to potential readers to mention the run times of MarkerScan.</p>
    <p> The discussion mentions higher false positive rates for FCS-GX. It may be helpful if the Authors could highlight these cases better already in the results section.</p>
    <p> At the cost of appearing self-promoting, I think the Authors should mention ContScout, a recent software that by far outperformed all prior contamination removal tools (Balint et al 2024 Nat. Comms). Though it works at the protein level, so may not be comparable to the tools used in this paper, it could be considered in the listing of contamination removal tools.</p>
    <p> On a sidenote I wonder if the Authors have discovered the irony of using a species called Mythimna impura in an analysis of genomic impurities.</p>
    <p>Is the rationale for developing the new method (or application) clearly explained?</p>
    <p>Yes</p>
    <p>Is the description of the method technically sound?</p>
    <p>Yes</p>
    <p>Are the conclusions about the method and its performance adequately supported by the findings presented in the article?</p>
    <p>Yes</p>
    <p>If any results are presented, are all the source data underlying the results available to ensure full reproducibility?</p>
    <p>Yes</p>
    <p>Are sufficient details provided to allow replication of the method development and its use by others?</p>
    <p>Yes</p>
    <p>Reviewer Expertise:</p>
    <p>bioinformatics, evolutionary genomics</p>
    <p>I confirm that I have read this submission and believe that I have an appropriate level of expertise to confirm that it is of an acceptable scientific standard, however I have significant reservations, as outlined above.</p>
  </body>
